{"title_page": "Elfrida (disambiguation)", "text_new": "'''Elfrida''' is a feminine given name - see [[Elfriede]]. '''Elfrida''' may also refer to:\n\n* [[Elfrida, Arizona]], an unincorporated community in the United States\n* [[618 Elfriede]], an asteroid\n*{{SS|Elfrida}}, a Norwegian cargo ship in service from 1947 to 1959\n*{{USS|Elfrida|SP-988}}, a United States Navy patrol vessel in commission in 1898, from 1899 to 1908, and from 1909 to 1918\n*''Elfrida'', a 1752 tragedy by [[William Mason (poet)|William Mason]]\n*''Elfrida'', a 1985 opera by Hungarian composer [[Erzs\u00e9bet Sz\u0151nyi]] (1924\u20132019)\n\n{{Disambiguation}}\n", "text_old": "'''Elfrida''' is a feminine given name - see [[Elfriede]]. '''Elfrida''' may also refer to:\n\n* [[Elfrida, Arizona]], an unincorporated community in the United States\n* [[618 Elfriede]], an asteroid\n*{{SS|Elfrida}}, a Norwegian cargo ship in service from 1947 to 1959\n*{{USS|Elfrida|SP-988}}, a United States Navy patrol vessel in commission in 1898, from 1899 to 1908, and from 1909 to 1918\n*''Elfrida'', a 1752 tragedy by [[William Mason (poet)|William Mason]]\n*''Elfrida'', a 1985 opera by Hungarian composer [[Erzs\u00e9bet Sz\u0151nyi]] (born 1924)\n\n{{Disambiguation}}\n", "name_user": "KR7907", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elfrida_(disambiguation)"}
{"title_page": "Wild Reeds", "text_new": "{{Infobox film\n|name            = Wild Reeds\n|image           = Les roseaux sauvages.jpg\n|caption         = Theatrical release poster\n|director        = [[Andr\u00e9 T\u00e9chin\u00e9]]\n|producer        = Georges Benayoun<br>[[Alain Sarde]]\n|writer          = Olivier Massart <br>Gilles Taurand<br> Andr\u00e9 T\u00e9chin\u00e9\n|starring        = [[\u00c9lodie Bouchez]]<br>[[Ga\u00ebl Morel]]<br>[[St\u00e9phane Rideau]]<br>[[Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Gorny]]\n|music           =\n|cinematography  = [[Jeanne Lapoirie]]\n|editing         = Martine Giordano\n|distributor     = Pan Europ\u00e9enne Distribution\n|released        = {{film date|1994|6|1|df=yes}}\n|runtime         = 110 minutes\n|country         = France\n|language        = French\n|budget          = $3.8 million\n|gross           = $5.2 million<ref>http://www.jpbox-office.com/fichfilm.php?id=4292</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Wild Reeds''''' ({{lang-fr|'''Les Roseaux sauvages'''}}) is a 1994 French [[Drama (film and television)|drama film]] directed by [[Andr\u00e9 T\u00e9chin\u00e9]] about the sexual awakening of four teenagers and their subsequent sensitive passage into adulthood at the end of the [[Algerian War of Independence|Algerian War]]. The film was selected as the French entry for the [[Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film|Best Foreign Language Film]] at the [[67th Academy Awards]], but not nominated.<ref>Margaret Herrick Library, Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nThe film is set in southwest France in 1962. Fran\u00e7ois ([[Ga\u00ebl Morel]]), a shy young man from the lower middle class, is working towards his high school diploma. He spends most of his time talking about movies and literature with his best friend, Ma\u00eft\u00e9 ([[\u00c9lodie Bouchez]]), whose mother Mme Alvarez ([[Mich\u00e8le Moretti]]) is Fran\u00e7ois's French teacher. Mme Alvarez and Ma\u00eft\u00e9 are communists. At the boarding school, Fran\u00e7ois becomes acquainted with Serge ([[St\u00e9phane Rideau]]), the sensual son of immigrant farmers. At night, he joins Fran\u00e7ois in the dormitory to chat. Finally, Serge draws Fran\u00e7ois into an erotic relationship.\n\nFran\u00e7ois discovers his homosexuality and develops a deep attraction for Serge, who had only acted out of curiosity. Fran\u00e7ois confides this discovery to Ma\u00eft\u00e9, who swallows her disappointment and encourages him to come out of the closet. When Serge becomes increasingly interested in Ma\u00eft\u00e9, she declares herself to be interested in nobody.\n\nSerge's brother Pierre dies while serving in the army in Algeria, and Ma\u00eft\u00e9's mother suffers a nervous breakdown, having previously refused to help Pierre desert. An Algerian-born French exile, Henri ([[Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Gorny]]), enrolls in the boys' boarding school and aggravates their conflicts, adding a political conflict. He is obsessed with events in Algeria and supports the [[Organisation de l'arm\u00e9e secr\u00e8te|OAS]], which opposes Algerian independence and defends the rights of French settlers there. He treats Fran\u00e7ois without sympathy and bluntly tells him to own up to his homosexuality. His political stance provokes Serge's hatred. Henri finally engages Ma\u00eft\u00e9, his political opposite, and they yield to their mutual attraction.\n\nEach member of the quartet develops in the course of the film, shifting repeatedly from stubborn positions to more flexible appreciations of their circumstances, explained in French class by a reading of \"[[The Oak and the Reed]]\", one of [[Aesop's Fables]].\n\n==Cast==\n* [[\u00c9lodie Bouchez]] as Ma\u00eft\u00e9 Alvarez\n* [[Ga\u00ebl Morel]] as Fran\u00e7ois Forestier\n* [[St\u00e9phane Rideau]] as Serge Bartolo\n* [[Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Gorny]] as Henri Mariani\n* [[Mich\u00e8le Moretti]] as Madame Alvarez\n* [[Jacques Nolot]] as Monsieur Morelli\n* Eric Kreikenmayer as Pierre Bartolo, the Groom\n* Nathalie Vignes as Ir\u00e8ne, the Bride\n* Michel Ruhl as Monsieur Cassagne\n* Fatia Maite as Aicha Morelli\n\n==Production==\nThe project was first conceived as part of a television film series dealing with adolescence, ''Tous les gar\u00e7ons et les filles de leurs \u00e2ges'', entitled ''Le ch\u00eane et le roseau'' (''The Oak and the Reed''), which made up the first 55 minutes of ''Wild Reeds''. But after completing the script, T\u00e9chin\u00e9 decided to make it a full theatrical release. Based on his own life story, it is his biggest personal success in France and his most intimate film.\n\nIt is one of limited number of films on the politically delicate subject of the Algerian War. They include ''[[The Little Soldier]]'' (1963), ''[[To Be Twenty in the Aures|Avoir vingt ans dans les Aur\u00e8s]]'' (1972), and ''La Question'' (1977).\n\n==Music==\n* \"[[Barbara Ann]]\" \u2013 [[The Beach Boys]]\n* ''[[Adagio for Strings]]'' \u2013 [[Samuel Barber]]\n* ''Wo die Zitronen bl\u00fchen'' & ''Fr\u00fchlingsstimmen'' \u2013 [[Johann Strauss II]]\n* \"[[Runaway (Del Shannon song)|Runaway]]\" \u2013 [[Del Shannon]]\n* \"[[Let's Twist Again]]\" \u2013 [[Chubby Checker]]\n* \"[[Smoke Gets in Your Eyes]]\" \u2013 [[The Platters]]\n* \"Soave sia il vento\" (from ''[[Cos\u00ec fan tutte]]'') - [[Mozart]]\n\n==Critical response==\nThe film was met with widespread critical acclaim and holds a rare 100% \"Fresh\" ratings on [[Rotten Tomatoes]].<ref name=\"Rotten Tomatoes\">http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/wild_reeds/</ref>  It was released in the United States on May 10, 1995 grossing $38,192 in 7 theaters its widest release eventually grossing a total of $917,915 in North America.<ref name=\"The Numbers\">http://www.the-numbers.com/movies/1995/0WIRE.php</ref> In France the film received limited release playing at a total of 40 cinemas and opening in second place in the French box office gaining 37,688 admissions its opening weekend. In total the film had 589,301 admissions in France and was the 51st highest earning film of the year.<ref name=\"JPBox Office\">http://www.jpbox-office.com/fichfilm.php?id=4292&affich=france&deplier=yes</ref>\n\n==Accolades==\n[[File:Ga\u00ebl Morel Elodie Bouchez.jpg|thumb|Stars [[Ga\u00ebl Morel]] and [[\u00c9lodie Bouchez]] promoting the film at the [[1994 Cannes Film Festival]].]]\nAt the 1995 [[C\u00e9sar Award]]s, ''Les Roseaux Sauvages'' won Best Film, Best Director ([[Andr\u00e9 T\u00e9chin\u00e9]]), Most Promising Young Actress ([[\u00c9lodie Bouchez]]) and Best Original Screenplay.\n\n*'''[[C\u00e9sar Awards]]''' (France)\n**'''Won''': Best Director (Andr\u00e9 T\u00e9chin\u00e9)\n**'''Won''': Best Film\n**'''Won''': Best Writing (Olivier Massart, Gilles Taurand and Andr\u00e9 T\u00e9chin\u00e9)\n**'''Won''': Most Promising Actress (\u00c9lodie Bouchez)\n**Nominated: Best Actress &ndash; Best Supporting Role (Mich\u00e8le Moretti)\n**Nominated: Most Promising Actor (Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Gorny)\n**Nominated: Most Promising Actor (Ga\u00ebl Morel)\n**Nominated: Most Promising Actor (St\u00e9phane Rideau)\n*'''[[Un Certain Regard]], [[1994 Cannes Film Festival|Cannes Film Festival]]''' (France)\n**Nominated<ref name=\"festival-cannes.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.festival-cannes.com/en/archives/ficheFilm/id/2996/year/1994.html |title=Festival de Cannes: Wild Reeds |accessdate=2009-08-31|work=festival-cannes.com}}</ref>\n*'''[[Los Angeles Film Critics Association|Los Angeles Film Critics]]''' (USA)\n**'''Won''': Best Foreign Language Film\n*'''[[National Society of Film Critics]]''' (USA)\n**'''Won''': Best Foreign Language Film\n*'''[[New York Film Critics Circle|New York Film Critics]]''' (USA)\n**'''Won''': Best Foreign Language Film\n*'''Won''': [[Louis Delluc Prize]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of submissions to the 67th Academy Awards for Best Foreign Language Film]]\n* [[List of French submissions for the Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* ''[http://frenchfilms.topcities.com/nf_Les_Roseaux_sauvages_rev.html Wild Reeds]'' at [http://filmsdefrance.com/ FilmsDeFrance.com]\n* {{IMDb title|0111019|Wild Reeds}}\n\n{{Andr\u00e9 T\u00e9chin\u00e9}}\n{{C\u00e9sar Award for Best Film}}\n{{French submission for Academy Awards}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wild Reeds (Film)}}\n[[Category:1990s drama films]]\n[[Category:1994 films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Andr\u00e9 T\u00e9chin\u00e9]]\n[[Category:French drama films]]\n[[Category:French films]]\n[[Category:French-language films]]\n[[Category:French LGBT-related films]]\n[[Category:Gay-related_films]]\n[[Category:1990s LGBT-related films]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1962]]\n[[Category:Louis Delluc Prize winners]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Alain Sarde]]\n[[Category:Juvenile sexuality in films]]\n[[Category:1990s coming-of-age films]]\n[[Category:Films whose director won the Best Director C\u00e9sar Award]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox film\n|name            = Wild Reeds\n|image           = Les roseaux sauvages.jpg\n|caption         = Theatrical release poster\n|director        = [[Andr\u00e9 T\u00e9chin\u00e9]]\n|producer        = Georges Benayoun<br>[[Alain Sarde]]\n|writer          = Olivier Massart <br>Gilles Taurand<br> Andr\u00e9 T\u00e9chin\u00e9\n|starring        = [[\u00c9lodie Bouchez]]<br>[[Ga\u00ebl Morel]]<br>[[St\u00e9phane Rideau]]<br>[[Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Gorny]]\n|music           =\n|cinematography  = [[Jeanne Lapoirie]]\n|editing         = Martine Giordano\n|distributor     = Pan Europ\u00e9enne Distribution\n|released        = {{film date|1994|6|1|df=yes}}\n|runtime         = 110 minutes\n|country         = France\n|language        = French\n|budget          = $3.8 million\n|gross           = $5.2 million<ref>http://www.jpbox-office.com/fichfilm.php?id=4292</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Wild Reeds''''' ({{lang-fr|'''Les Roseaux sauvages'''}}) is a 1994 French [[Drama (film and television)|drama film]] directed by [[Andr\u00e9 T\u00e9chin\u00e9]] about the sexual awakening of four teenagers and their subsequent sensitive passage into adulthood at the end of the [[Algerian War of Independence|Algerian War]]. The film was selected as the French entry for the [[Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film|Best Foreign Language Film]] at the [[67th Academy Awards]], but not nominated.<ref>Margaret Herrick Library, Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nThe film is set in southwest France in 1962. Fran\u00e7ois ([[Ga\u00ebl Morel]]), a shy young man from the lower middle class, is working towards his high school diploma. He spends most of his time talking about movies and literature with his best friend, Ma\u00eft\u00e9 ([[\u00c9lodie Bouchez]]), whose mother Mme Alvarez ([[Mich\u00e8le Moretti]]) is Fran\u00e7ois's French teacher. Mme Alvarez and Ma\u00eft\u00e9 are communists. At the boarding school, Fran\u00e7ois becomes acquainted with Serge ([[St\u00e9phane Rideau]]), the sensual son of immigrant farmers. At night, he joins Fran\u00e7ois in the dormitory to chat. Finally, Serge draws Fran\u00e7ois into an erotic relationship.\n\nFran\u00e7ois discovers his homosexuality and develops a deep attraction for Serge, who had only acted out of curiosity. Fran\u00e7ois confides this discovery to Ma\u00eft\u00e9, who swallows her disappointment and encourages him to come out of the closet. When Serge becomes increasingly interested in Ma\u00eft\u00e9, she declares herself to be interested in nobody.\n\nSerge's brother Pierre dies while serving in the army in Algeria, and Ma\u00eft\u00e9's mother suffers a nervous breakdown, having previously refused to help Pierre desert. An Algerian-born French exile, Henri ([[Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Gorny]]), enrolls in the boys' boarding school and aggravates their conflicts, adding a political conflict. He is obsessed with events in Algeria and supports the [[Organisation de l'arm\u00e9e secr\u00e8te|OAS]], which opposes Algerian independence and defends the rights of French settlers there. He treats Fran\u00e7ois without sympathy and bluntly tells him to own up to his homosexuality. His political stance provokes Serge's hatred. Henri finally engages Ma\u00eft\u00e9, his political opposite, and they yield to their mutual attraction.\n\nEach member of the quartet develops in the course of the film, shifting repeatedly from stubborn positions to more flexible appreciations of their circumstances, explained in French class by a reading of \"[[The Oak and the Reed]]\", one of [[Aesop's Fables]].\n\n==Cast==\n* [[\u00c9lodie Bouchez]] as Ma\u00eft\u00e9 Alvarez\n* [[Ga\u00ebl Morel]] as Fran\u00e7ois Forestier\n* [[St\u00e9phane Rideau]] as Serge Bartolo\n* [[Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Gorny]] as Henri Mariani\n* [[Mich\u00e8le Moretti]] as Madame Alvarez\n* [[Jacques Nolot]] as Monsieur Morelli\n* Eric Kreikenmayer as Pierre Bartolo, the Groom\n* Nathalie Vignes as Ir\u00e8ne, the Bride\n* Michel Ruhl as Monsieur Cassagne\n* Fatia Maite as Aicha Morelli\n\n==Production==\nThe project was first conceived as part of a television film series dealing with adolescence, ''Tous les gar\u00e7ons et les filles de leurs \u00e2ges'', entitled ''Le ch\u00eane et le roseau'' (''The Oak and the Reed''), which made up the first 55 minutes of ''Wild Reeds''. But after completing the script, T\u00e9chin\u00e9 decided to make it a full theatrical release. Based on his own life story, it is his biggest personal success in France and his most intimate film.\n\nIt is one of limited number of films on the politically delicate subject of the Algerian War. They include ''[[The Little Soldier]]'' (1963), ''[[To Be Twenty in the Aures|Avoir vingt ans dans les Aur\u00e8s]]'' (1972), and ''La Question'' (1977).\n\n==Music==\n* \"[[Barbara Ann]]\" \u2013 [[The Beach Boys]]\n* ''[[Adagio for Strings]]'' \u2013 [[Samuel Barber]]\n* ''Wo die Zitronen bl\u00fchen'' & ''Fr\u00fchlingsstimmen'' \u2013 [[Johann Strauss II]]\n* \"[[Runaway (Del Shannon song)|Runaway]]\" \u2013 [[Del Shannon]]\n* \"[[Let's Twist Again]]\" \u2013 [[Chubby Checker]]\n* \"[[Smoke Gets in Your Eyes]]\" \u2013 [[The Platters]]\n* \"Soave sia il vento\" (from ''[[Cos\u00ec fan tutte]]'') - [[Mozart]]\n\n==Critical response==\nThe film was met with widespread critical acclaim and holds a rare 100% \"Fresh\" ratings on [[Rotten Tomatoes]].<ref name=\"Rotten Tomatoes\">http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/wild_reeds/</ref>  It was released in the United States on May 10, 1995 grossing $38,192 in 7 theaters its widest release eventually grossing a total of $917,915 in North America.<ref name=\"The Numbers\">http://www.the-numbers.com/movies/1995/0WIRE.php</ref> In France the film received limited release playing at a total of 40 cinemas and opening in second place in the French box office gaining 37,688 admissions its opening weekend. In total the film had 589,301 admissions in France and was the 51st highest earning film of the year.<ref name=\"JPBox Office\">http://www.jpbox-office.com/fichfilm.php?id=4292&affich=france&deplier=yes</ref>\n\n==Accolades==\n[[File:Ga\u00ebl Morel Elodie Bouchez.jpg|thumb|Stars [[Ga\u00ebl Morel]] and [[\u00c9lodie Bouchez]] promoting the film at the [[1994 Cannes Film Festival]].]]\nAt the 1995 [[C\u00e9sar Award]]s, ''Les Roseaux Sauvages'' won Best Film, Best Director ([[Andr\u00e9 T\u00e9chin\u00e9]]), Most Promising Young Actress ([[\u00c9lodie Bouchez]]) and Best Original Screenplay.\n\n*'''[[C\u00e9sar Awards]]''' (France)\n**'''Won''': Best Director (Andr\u00e9 T\u00e9chin\u00e9)\n**'''Won''': Best Film\n**'''Won''': Best Writing (Olivier Massart, Gilles Taurand and Andr\u00e9 T\u00e9chin\u00e9)\n**'''Won''': Most Promising Actress (\u00c9lodie Bouchez)\n**Nominated: Best Actress &ndash; Best Supporting Role (Mich\u00e8le Moretti)\n**Nominated: Most Promising Actor (Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Gorny)\n**Nominated: Most Promising Actor (Ga\u00ebl Morel)\n**Nominated: Most Promising Actor (St\u00e9phane Rideau)\n*'''[[Un Certain Regard]], [[1994 Cannes Film Festival|Cannes Film Festival]]''' (France)\n**Nominated<ref name=\"festival-cannes.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.festival-cannes.com/en/archives/ficheFilm/id/2996/year/1994.html |title=Festival de Cannes: Wild Reeds |accessdate=2009-08-31|work=festival-cannes.com}}</ref>\n*'''[[Los Angeles Film Critics Association|Los Angeles Film Critics]]''' (USA)\n**'''Won''': Best Foreign Language Film\n*'''[[National Society of Film Critics]]''' (USA)\n**'''Won''': Best Foreign Language Film\n*'''[[New York Film Critics Circle|New York Film Critics]]''' (USA)\n**'''Won''': Best Foreign Language Film\n*'''Won''': [[Louis Delluc Prize]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of submissions to the 67th Academy Awards for Best Foreign Language Film]]\n* [[List of French submissions for the Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* ''[http://frenchfilms.topcities.com/nf_Les_Roseaux_sauvages_rev.html Wild Reeds]'' at [http://filmsdefrance.com/ FilmsDeFrance.com]\n* {{IMDb title|0111019|Wild Reeds}}\n\n{{Andr\u00e9 T\u00e9chin\u00e9}}\n{{C\u00e9sar Award for Best Film}}\n{{French submission for Academy Awards}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wild Reeds (Film)}}\n[[Category:1990s drama films]]\n[[Category:1994 films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Andr\u00e9 T\u00e9chin\u00e9]]\n[[Category:French drama films]]\n[[Category:French films]]\n[[Category:French-language films]]\n[[Category:French LGBT-related films]]\n[[Category:Gay-related_films]]\n[[Category:1990s LGBT-related films]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1962]]\n[[Category:Louis Delluc Prize winners]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Alain Sarde]]\n[[Category:Juvenile sexuality in films]]\n[[Category:1990s coming-of-age films]]\n", "name_user": "Diopic", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:addCategory:Films whose director won the Best Director C\u00e9sar Award", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wild_Reeds"}
{"title_page": "MACS0647-JD", "text_new": "__NOTOC__{{ Infobox Galaxy\n| image = MACS0647-JD.JPG\n| image_size = 250px\n| caption = [[Hubble Space Telescope]] image of MACS0647-JD\n| name = MACS0647-JD\n| epoch = [[J2000]]\n| type = dIrr?\n| mass = 4.82\u00d710^85 kg\n| ra = {{RA|06|47|55.73}}\n| dec = {{DEC|+70|14|35.8}}\n| dist_ly = 13.3 [[1,000,000,000|billion]] [[light year]]s (4.1 billion parsecs) (light-travel time) <br />32 [[1,000,000,000|billion]] [[light year]]s (10 billion parsecs) (comoving distance)\n| stars = 1 billion (1\u00d710<sup>9</sup>)\n| group_cluster = [[MACS J0647+7015]]\n| z = 10.7\n| appmag_v = \n| size_v = 0.00015 x 0.00015\n| constellation name = [[Camelopardalis (constellation)|Camelopardalis]]\n| size = 600 ly (diameter)\n| notes = \n| names = CZC2013 MACS0647-JD1\n}}\n'''MACS0647-JD''' is the second [[List of the most distant astronomical objects|farthest]] known [[galaxy]] from the [[Earth]] based on the [[photometric redshift]]. It has a [[redshift]] of about ''z'' = 10.7, equivalent to a light travel distance of 13.26 billion [[light-year]]s (4 billion [[parsec]]s). If the distance estimate is correct, it formed about 427 million years after the [[Big Bang]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hubblesite.org/newscenter/archive/releases/2012/36 |work=[[Space Telescope Science Institute]] |title=NASA Great Observatories Find Candidate for Most Distant Galaxy Yet Known |date=November 15, 2012 |accessdate=November 17, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | bibcode = 2013ApJ...762...32C | title=CLASH: Three Strongly Lensed Images of a Candidate z ~ 11 Galaxy | journal=The Astrophysical Journal | volume=762 | issue=1 | page=32 | year=2013 | doi=10.1088/0004-637x/762/1/32|arxiv = 1211.3663 | last1=Coe | first1=Dan | last2=Weasley | first2=Adi | last3=Carrasco | first3=Mauricio | last4=Shu | first4=Potter | last5=Zheng | first5=Wei | last6=Postman | first6=Malfoy | last7=Bradley | first7=Larry | last8=Koekemoer | first8=Anton | last9=Bouwens | first9=Dumbledore | last10=Broadhurst | first10=Tom | last11=Granger | first11=Anna | last12=Host | first12=Hole | last13=Moustakas | first13=Leonidas A. | last14=Ford | first14=Holland | last15=Moustakas | first15=John | last16=Van Der Wel | first16=Arjen | last17=Donahue | first17=Megan | last18=Rodney | first18=Steven A. | last19=Ben\u00edtez | first19=Narciso | last20=Jouvel | first20=Stephanie | last21=Seitz | first21=Stella | last22=Kelson | first22=Daniel D. | last23=Rosati | first23=Piero }}</ref><ref name=\"Coe\"/><ref name=heic>{{cite web |url=http://www.spacetelescope.org/images/heic1217b/ |title=Hubble spots three magnified views of most distant known galaxy |work=[[Hubble Space Telescope]] |date=November 15, 2012 |accessdate=November 17, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"D. Coe\">{{cite book |url=http://www.stsci.edu/~dcoe/z11/|author=D. Coe|title=Hubble Spies ...] |publisher=[[Astrophysical Journal]]|accessdate=2015-11-02}}</ref>[[File:Hubble spots candidate for most distant known galaxy.jpg|thumb|MACS0647-JD is very young and only a tiny fraction of the size of the [[Milky Way]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Hubble helps find candidate for most distant object in the Universe yet observed|url=http://www.spacetelescope.org/news/heic1217/|accessdate=15 February 2013|newspaper=ESA/Hubble Press Release}}</ref> |alt=|left]]\n\n==Details==\nJD refers to ''J-band Dropout'' \u2013 the galaxy was not detected in the so-called J-band (F125W), nor in 14 bluer Hubble filters. It only appeared in the two reddest filters (F140W and F160W).\n\nIt is less than 600 light-years wide, and contains roughly a billion stars.\n\nThe galaxy was discovered with the help of [[Cluster Lensing And Supernova survey with Hubble]] (CLASH), which uses massive [[galaxy cluster]]s as cosmic telescopes to magnify distant galaxies behind them, an effect called [[gravitational lensing]]. Observations were recorded by the [[Wide Field Camera 3]] on the [[Hubble Space Telescope]],<ref name=heic/> with support from [[Spitzer Space Telescope]].<ref name=\"Coe\"/>\n\nThe location of the galaxy is in the constellation [[Camelopardalis]], which is also the location of the gravitational lensing cluster that helped discover this galaxy: [[MACSJ0647+7015]] at ''z'' = 0.591.<ref>{{cite web |title=NASA Great Observatories Find Candidate for Most Distant Galaxy Yet Known |url=http://hubblesite.org/newscenter/archive/releases/2012/36/fastfacts/ |work=Space Telescope Science Institute |series=Fast Facts |date=November 15, 2012 |accessdate=November 17, 2012}}</ref>\n\nMACS0647-JD was announced in November 2012, but by the next month [[UDFj-39546284]], which was previously thought to be ''z'' = 10.3, was said to be at ''z'' = 11.9,<ref>[http://www.universetoday.com/98959/hubble-census-unveils-galaxies-shining-near-cosmic-dawn/#more-98959 Universe Today - Hubble Census Unveils Galaxies Shining Near Cosmic Dawn]</ref> although more recent analyses have suggested the latter is likely to be at a lower redshift.<ref>{{cite journal | bibcode = 2013ApJ...765L...2B | title=A Tentative Detection of an Emission Line at 1.6 mum for the z ~ 12 Candidate UDFj-39546284 | journal=The Astrophysical Journal | volume=765 | issue=1 | page=L2 | year=2013 | doi=10.1088/2041-8205/765/1/l2|arxiv = 1301.0317 | last1=Brammer | first1=Gabriel B. | last2=Van Dokkum | first2=Pieter G. | last3=Illingworth | first3=Garth D. | last4=Bouwens | first4=Rychard J. | last5=Labb\u00e9 | first5=Ivo | last6=Franx | first6=Marijn | last7=Momcheva | first7=Ivelina | last8=Oesch | first8=Pascal A. | last9=Bouwens | first9=Rychard | last10=Broadhurst | first10=Tom | last11=Monna | first11=Anna | last12=Host | first12=Ole | last13=Moustakas | first13=Leonidas A. | last14=Ford | first14=Holland | last15=Moustakas | first15=John | author16=Arjen van der Wel | last17=Donahue | first17=Megan | last18=Rodney | first18=Steven A. | last19=Benitez | first19=Narciso | last20=Jouvel | first20=Stephanie | last21=Seitz | first21=Stella | last22=Kelson | first22=Daniel D. | last23=Rosati | first23=Piero }}</ref> Spectroscopic confirmation of the redshift of MACS0647-JD likely awaits the launch of the [[James Webb Space Telescope]] expected in 2021.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://scitechdaily.com/hubble-views-what-is-probably-the-most-distant-known-galaxy/ | title=Hubble Views What is Probably the Most Distant Known Galaxy| date=2012-11-16}}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\nA confirming paper was published in the December 20, 2012 issue of ''[[The Astrophysical Journal]]''. A preprint of the paper is available on [[arXiv]].<ref name=\"Coe\"/>\n\nPhotometric [[redshift]] ''z'' = 10.7 +0.6 / \u22120.4 (95% confidence limits; with ''z'' < 9.5 galaxies of known types ruled out at 7.2-sigma).<ref name=\"Coe\">{{cite journal |first=Dan |display-authors=etal |last=Coe |title=CLASH: Three Strongly Lensed Images of a Candidate z ~ 11 Galaxy |arxiv=1211.3663|date=November 15, 2012 |doi=10.1088/0004-637X/762/1/32 |volume=762 |issue=1 |journal=The Astrophysical Journal |page=32 |bibcode=2013ApJ...762...32C}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of the most distant astronomical objects]]\n* [[List of galaxies#Farthest galaxies|Farthest galaxies]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{commonscat-inline}}\n* [http://www.nasa.gov/mission_pages/hubble/science/distance-record.html NASA Great Observatories Find Candidate for Most Distant Object in the Universe to Date]\n* [[European Space Agency]] \u2013 [http://sci.esa.int/jump.cfm?oid=51112 Galaxy cluster MACS J0647.7+7015]\n\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[UDFj-39546284]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of the most distant astronomical objects|Most distant astronomical object known]]|years=2012}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[UDFj-39546284]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[UDFj-39546284]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of galaxies#Farthest galaxies|Most distant galaxy known]]|years=2012}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[UDFj-39546284]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Camelopardalis|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:MACS0647-JD}}\n[[Category:Galaxies]]\n[[Category:Camelopardalis (constellation)]]\n[[Category:Dwarf galaxies]]\n", "text_old": "__NOTOC__{{ Infobox Galaxy\n| image = MACS0647-JD.JPG\n| image_size = 250px\n| caption = [[Hubble Space Telescope]] image of MACS0647-JD\n| name = MACS0647-JD\n| epoch = [[J2000]]\n| type = dwarf\n| mass = 4.82\u00d710^85 kg\n| ra = {{RA|06|47|55.73}}\n| dec = {{DEC|+70|14|35.8}}\n| dist_ly = 13.3 [[1,000,000,000|on]] [[light year]]s (light-travel time) <br />32 [[1,000,000,000|billion]] [[light year]]s (comoving distance)\n| stars = 1 billion (1\u00d710<sup>9</sup>)\n| group_cluster = [[MACS J0647+7015]]\n| z = 10.7\n| appmag_v = \n| size_v = 0.00015 x 0.00015\n| constellation name = [[Camelopardalis (constellation)|Camelopardalis]]\n| size = 600 ly (diameter)\n| notes = \n| names = CZC2013 MACS0647-JD1\n}}\n'''MACS0647-JD''' is the second [[List of the most distant astronomical objects|farthest]] known [[galaxy]] from the [[Earth]] based on the [[photometric redshift]]. It has a [[redshift]] of about ''z'' = 10.7, equivalent to a light travel distance of 13.26 billion [[light-year]]s (4 billion [[parsec]]s). If the distance estimate is correct, it formed about 427 million years after the [[Big Bang]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hubblesite.org/newscenter/archive/releases/2012/36 |work=[[Space Telescope Science Institute]] |title=NASA Great Observatories Find Candidate for Most Distant Galaxy Yet Known |date=November 15, 2012 |accessdate=November 17, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | bibcode = 2013ApJ...762...32C | title=CLASH: Three Strongly Lensed Images of a Candidate z ~ 11 Galaxy | journal=The Astrophysical Journal | volume=762 | issue=1 | page=32 | year=2013 | doi=10.1088/0004-637x/762/1/32|arxiv = 1211.3663 | last1=Coe | first1=Dan | last2=Weasley | first2=Adi | last3=Carrasco | first3=Mauricio | last4=Shu | first4=Potter | last5=Zheng | first5=Wei | last6=Postman | first6=Malfoy | last7=Bradley | first7=Larry | last8=Koekemoer | first8=Anton | last9=Bouwens | first9=Dumbledore | last10=Broadhurst | first10=Tom | last11=Granger | first11=Anna | last12=Host | first12=Hole | last13=Moustakas | first13=Leonidas A. | last14=Ford | first14=Holland | last15=Moustakas | first15=John | last16=Van Der Wel | first16=Arjen | last17=Donahue | first17=Megan | last18=Rodney | first18=Steven A. | last19=Ben\u00edtez | first19=Narciso | last20=Jouvel | first20=Stephanie | last21=Seitz | first21=Stella | last22=Kelson | first22=Daniel D. | last23=Rosati | first23=Piero }}</ref><ref name=\"Coe\"/><ref name=heic>{{cite web |url=http://www.spacetelescope.org/images/heic1217b/ |title=Hubble spots three magnified views of most distant known galaxy |work=[[Hubble Space Telescope]] |date=November 15, 2012 |accessdate=November 17, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"D. Coe\">{{cite book |url=http://www.stsci.edu/~dcoe/z11/|author=D. Coe|title=Hubble Spies ...] |publisher=[[Astrophysical Journal]]|accessdate=2015-11-02}}</ref>[[File:Hubble spots candidate for most distant known galaxy.jpg|thumb|MACS0647-JD is very young and only a tiny fraction of the size of the [[Milky Way]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Hubble helps find candidate for most distant object in the Universe yet observed|url=http://www.spacetelescope.org/news/heic1217/|accessdate=15 February 2013|newspaper=ESA/Hubble Press Release}}</ref> |alt=|left]]\n\n==Details==\nJD refers to ''J-band Dropout'' \u2013 the galaxy was not detected in the so-called J-band (F125W), nor in 14 bluer Hubble filters. It only appeared in the two reddest filters (F140W and F160W).\n\nIt is less than 600 light-years wide, and contains roughly a billion stars.\n\nThe galaxy was discovered with the help of [[Cluster Lensing And Supernova survey with Hubble]] (CLASH), which uses massive [[galaxy cluster]]s as cosmic telescopes to magnify distant galaxies behind them, an effect called [[gravitational lensing]]. Observations were recorded by the [[Wide Field Camera 3]] on the [[Hubble Space Telescope]],<ref name=heic/> with support from [[Spitzer Space Telescope]].<ref name=\"Coe\"/>\n\nThe location of the galaxy is in the constellation [[Camelopardalis]], which is also the location of the gravitational lensing cluster that helped discover this galaxy: [[MACSJ0647+7015]] at ''z'' = 0.591.<ref>{{cite web |title=NASA Great Observatories Find Candidate for Most Distant Galaxy Yet Known |url=http://hubblesite.org/newscenter/archive/releases/2012/36/fastfacts/ |work=Space Telescope Science Institute |series=Fast Facts |date=November 15, 2012 |accessdate=November 17, 2012}}</ref>\n\nMACS0647-JD was announced in November 2012, but by the next month [[UDFj-39546284]], which was previously thought to be ''z'' = 10.3, was said to be at ''z'' = 11.9,<ref>[http://www.universetoday.com/98959/hubble-census-unveils-galaxies-shining-near-cosmic-dawn/#more-98959 Universe Today - Hubble Census Unveils Galaxies Shining Near Cosmic Dawn]</ref> although more recent analyses have suggested the latter is likely to be at a lower redshift.<ref>{{cite journal | bibcode = 2013ApJ...765L...2B | title=A Tentative Detection of an Emission Line at 1.6 mum for the z ~ 12 Candidate UDFj-39546284 | journal=The Astrophysical Journal | volume=765 | issue=1 | page=L2 | year=2013 | doi=10.1088/2041-8205/765/1/l2|arxiv = 1301.0317 | last1=Brammer | first1=Gabriel B. | last2=Van Dokkum | first2=Pieter G. | last3=Illingworth | first3=Garth D. | last4=Bouwens | first4=Rychard J. | last5=Labb\u00e9 | first5=Ivo | last6=Franx | first6=Marijn | last7=Momcheva | first7=Ivelina | last8=Oesch | first8=Pascal A. | last9=Bouwens | first9=Rychard | last10=Broadhurst | first10=Tom | last11=Monna | first11=Anna | last12=Host | first12=Ole | last13=Moustakas | first13=Leonidas A. | last14=Ford | first14=Holland | last15=Moustakas | first15=John | author16=Arjen van der Wel | last17=Donahue | first17=Megan | last18=Rodney | first18=Steven A. | last19=Benitez | first19=Narciso | last20=Jouvel | first20=Stephanie | last21=Seitz | first21=Stella | last22=Kelson | first22=Daniel D. | last23=Rosati | first23=Piero }}</ref> Spectroscopic confirmation of the redshift of MACS0647-JD likely awaits the launch of the [[James Webb Space Telescope]] expected in 2021.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://scitechdaily.com/hubble-views-what-is-probably-the-most-distant-known-galaxy/ | title=Hubble Views What is Probably the Most Distant Known Galaxy| date=2012-11-16}}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\nA confirming paper was published in the December 20, 2012 issue of ''[[The Astrophysical Journal]]''. A preprint of the paper is available on [[arXiv]].<ref name=\"Coe\"/>\n\nPhotometric [[redshift]] ''z'' = 10.7 +0.6 / \u22120.4 (95% confidence limits; with ''z'' < 9.5 galaxies of known types ruled out at 7.2-sigma).<ref name=\"Coe\">{{cite journal |first=Dan |display-authors=etal |last=Coe |title=CLASH: Three Strongly Lensed Images of a Candidate z ~ 11 Galaxy |arxiv=1211.3663|date=November 15, 2012 |doi=10.1088/0004-637X/762/1/32 |volume=762 |issue=1 |journal=The Astrophysical Journal |page=32 |bibcode=2013ApJ...762...32C}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of the most distant astronomical objects]]\n* [[List of galaxies#Farthest galaxies|Farthest galaxies]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{commonscat-inline}}\n* [http://www.nasa.gov/mission_pages/hubble/science/distance-record.html NASA Great Observatories Find Candidate for Most Distant Object in the Universe to Date]\n* [[European Space Agency]] \u2013 [http://sci.esa.int/jump.cfm?oid=51112 Galaxy cluster MACS J0647.7+7015]\n\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[UDFj-39546284]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of the most distant astronomical objects|Most distant astronomical object known]]|years=2012}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[UDFj-39546284]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[UDFj-39546284]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of galaxies#Farthest galaxies|Most distant galaxy known]]|years=2012}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[UDFj-39546284]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Camelopardalis|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:M