layers]]\n[[Category:Liverpool F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Scottish Junior Football Association players]]\n[[Category:Scottish Football League players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Scottish league football top scorers]]\n[[Category:UEFA Champions League winning players]]\n[[Category:English Football Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:Scottish Football Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:Scottish Sports Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:Scotland under-23 international footballers]]\n[[Category:Scotland international footballers]]\n[[Category:1974 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:1978 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:1982 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:FIFA Century Club]]\n[[Category:FIFA 100]]\n[[Category:Association football player-managers]]\n[[Category:Scottish football managers]]\n[[Category:Liverpool F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:Blackburn Rovers F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:Newcastle United F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:Celtic F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:English Football League managers]]\n[[Category:Premier League managers]]\n[[Category:Scottish Premier League managers]]\n[[Category:Football players and officials awarded knighthoods]]\n[[Category:Knights Bachelor]]\n[[Category:Members of the Order of the British Empire]]\n", "name_user": "109.255.39.16", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(latest)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kenny_Dalglish"}
{"title_page": "Buhl Airsedan", "text_new": "<!-- This article is a part of [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Aircraft]]. Please see [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Aircraft/page content]] for recommended layout. -->\n{{short description|1927 American single-engine sesquiplane cabin light transport aircraft}}\n{|{{Infobox Aircraft Begin\n |name= Airsedan\n |image= File:Buhl CA-5 NC3763 in flight showing undersides (cropped).jpg \n |caption= CA-5 Air Sedan ''The Angeleno''\n}}{{Infobox Aircraft Type\n |type= Civil utility aircraft\n |manufacturer= [[Buhl Aircraft Company]]\n |designer= [[Etienne Dormoy]]<ref name=Aerofiles>{{cite web|last=Eckland|first=K. O.|url=http://www.aerofiles.com/_buhl.html|title=Buhl, Buhl-Verville|work=Aerofiles.com|date=13 October 2008|accessdate=28 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n |first flight= [[1927 in aviation|1927]]\n |introduced= 1927\n |retired=\n |status=Retired\n |primary user= [[Nick Mamer|Mamer Air Transport/Flying Service]] \n |more users =[[Ontario Provincial Air Service|Ontario Provincial Air Service (OPAS)]]<br/>[[Carlos Panini|Servicio A\u00e9reo Panini]]\n |produced= 1927-1937\n |unit cost = $11,000 (CA-3C) to $19,500 (CA-8A)<ref name=Aerofiles/>\n |number built= 62+ (20 x CA-3, 14 x CA-5, 23 x CA-6, 5 x CA-8)\n}}\n|}\n[[File:Etienne Dormoy.jpg|thumb|Etienne Dormoy with Buhl CA-8]]\n[[File:Unmarked Buhl CA-5 Airsedan prototype (cropped).jpg|thumb|Unmarked CA-5 Airsedan prototype]]\n<!--[[File:Buhl CA-5 Airsedan NX2915 Miss Doran Dole racer.jpg|thumb|CA-5 ''Miss Doran'' NX2915 preparing for the Dole race]]-->\nThe '''Buhl AirSedan''' was a family of [[United States|American]] civil cabin [[sesquiplane]] aircraft developed and manufactured by the [[Buhl Aircraft Company]] in the late 1920s. One example completed the first transcontinental non-stop roundtrip flight, made in 1929 by the CA-6 ''Spokane Sun-God'',<ref name=Meister>{{cite web|last=Meister Jr.|first=Richard L.|url=http://www.aerofiles.com/sungod.html|title=The Flight of the Buhl Airsedan Spokane Sun-God|date=February 2000|accessdate=28 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and the first [[Pope]] to have flown did so in a Buhl Airsedan.<ref name=goldenwingsmuseum/>\n\n==Design and development==\nThe Airsedan series were designed by [[Etienne Dormoy]] following the departure of [[Alfred V. Verville]] from Buhl, with whom he had worked previously. Dormoy had worked with [[Deperdussin]] before [[World War one]], flew combat operations during the war before returning to work with [[Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 pour l'aviation et ses d\u00e9riv\u00e9s|SPAD]], travelled to the US to coordinate production of SPADs with [[Curtiss Aeroplane and Motor Company|Curtiss]] until the project was cancelled with the end of the war. He then worked with [[Packard]] on automobiles for a year in 1919 before working as a civilian with the [[United States Army Air Corps]] with Verville, who convinced him to work at Buhl.<ref name=Bleneau1>Bleneau, Les berlines Buhl  (Premi\u00e8re partie), p.2-3</ref> As a Frenchman, he was familiar with the advantages of the sesquiplane concept as it was a popular configuration in France, such as with the [[Breguet 26T]] airliner, but rare in the US.<ref name=Bleneau1/>\n\nThe fuselage framework, lower wing and [[empennage]] were welded [[41xx steel|chromium-molybdenum alloy steel]] tubes faired with wooden battens, with the lower wing integral with the fuselage structure.<ref name=Juptner1962p44/> The upper wings were built around spruce spars, with built up ribs made from spruce and plywood. The entire airframe was covered with [[Aircraft dope|dope]]d aircraft-grade fabric.<ref name=Juptner1962p44/>\nTo reduce control forces, projecting aerodynamic balance horns on rudder and elevators, while inset aerodynamic horns were used on the ailerons, which were fitted to the upper wing only.<ref name=Juptner1962p44/> To provide trim control, the rudder was ground adjustable while the elevators could be adjustable in flight.<ref name=Juptner1962p44/> Depending on the models, three different designs of lower wings were used - either constant chord with reversed N struts on the CA-5, a triangular wing with a vee strut on the CA-3, CA-6 and CA-8, or a constant chord wing with two rigged struts, on Canadian built CA-6Ms.\nAll were conventional [[sesquiplane]]s with fully enclosed [[cockpit]]s, fitted with dual controls in front of a passenger cabin. The number in the designation generally referred to the number of occupants as originally designed, with a larger number of seats corresponding to a larger airframe. \nThe first variant built was the CA-5, while later variants had a much slimmer [[fuselage]], a greatly improved windscreen design and a modified cockpit. The CA-5 had the undercarriage legs connected to the fuselage, and part way out from the fuselage, on the lower wing. The CA-3 had the undercarriage mounted solely to the fuselage, while the CA-6 and CA-8 had additional bracing struts from the top of the fuselage to the lower wing which allowed the undercarriage track to be widened. Buhl asserted that its undercarriage design reduced camber changes during landing, and the tendency to yaw due to bumpy ground. The CA-6 was certified to use [[Edo Aircraft Corporation|Edo J-5300 floats]].<ref name=CAHS>Anderson, 1990, p.20</ref>\n\n===Canadian production===\n[[File:Buhl Airsedan CA-6M CF-OAR, Ontario Provincial Air Service, front port side.jpg|thumb|Canadian-built Buhl CA-6M Airsedan with enlarged lower wings.]]\nAfter Buhl had ceased operations in 1932 due to declining sales as the [[Great Depression]] deepened, the drawings and jigs were purchased by the [[Ontario Provincial Air Service|Ontario Provincial Air Service (OPAS)]] in [[Canada]] who then built four CA-6M's for use as fire spotting aircraft at their facility in [[Sault Ste. Marie, Ontario|Sault Ste. Marie]] between 1935 and 1937. These differed from the original aircraft in having [[Canadian Vickers]] floats, a new fin and rudder and larger lower wings.<ref name=OPAS>{{cite web|author=Various|title=Government Of Ontario Buhl Air Sedan|url=https://www.bushplane.com/opas-aircraft/histories-opas-buhl/|work=www.bushplane.com|date=2011\u20132018|accessdate=15 January 2020}}</ref> Due to the excessive weight of the Canadian-Vickers built floats, the first [[Ontario Provincial Air Service]]-built CA-6M refused to leave the water until given a more powerful {{cvt|440|hp}} [[Pratt & Whitney Wasp]] engine.\n\n==Operational history==\n[[File:Buhl CA-3C The Angelino Junior NC7448 Oakland-Cleveland race August 1929.jpg|thumb|''The Angelino Junior'' after winning the 1929 Oakland-Cleveland race]]\n[[File:Buhl CA-5 Air Sedan NR3763 The Angeleno in flight.jpg|thumb|''The Angeleno'' (L) being refueled in flight from a [[Curtiss Carrier Pigeon]]]]\n[[File:Buhl CA-6 Air Sedan. Spokane Sun God (cropped).jpg|thumb|CA-6 Air Sedan ''Spokane Sun God'' after non-stop round trip crossing of the United States]]\nA CA-5 Airsedan NC2915, dubbed ''Miss Doran'', and flown by [[Auggie Pedlar]] with [[V. P. Knope]] navigating, was one of the entrants in the disastrous August 1927 [[Dole Air Race]] and like many competitors, was lost at sea.<ref name=Aerofiles/><ref name=Juptner1962p44/> Two other aviators lost their lives in a Swallow monoplane while searching for them. <ref name=Juptner1962p44/>\n\nA CA-3C Sport Airsedan NC7448, named ''Angelino Jr'' was piloted by [[Loren Mendell]] to first place in the [[National Air Race|Oakland-Cleveland Air Derby during the 1929 National Air Races]].<ref name=Aerofiles/>\n\n''The Angeleno'', CA-5A NR3763, set an endurance record of 246 hours, 43 minutes and 2 seconds on July 12th 1929 using [[inflight refuelling]].<ref name=Juptner1962p96/> They had just barely beaten the previous record when trash tossed from the aircraft jammed the tail and ended their run - and worse, their record would be bested within two weeks with a [[Curtiss Robin]].<ref name=Parks>Parks, 2015, p.25</ref>\n\nAnother Airsedan, a CA-6 Special NC9628 named ''Spokane Sun God'' made the first nonstop round-trip crossing the United States by air. [[Nick Mamer]] and [[Art Walker (aviator)|Art Walker]] flew from [[Spokane, Washington]] to [[New York City]] and back from between the 15th and 21st of August 1929, taking 120 hours, 1 minute and 40 seconds for the trip, using inflight refuelling.<ref name=Meister/> They covered {{cvt|7200|miles}} and made 11 fuel transfers.<ref name=Juptner1964p81/> That was not Nick Mamer's only connection to the Airsedans, as his airlines operated five examples in addition to the record breaking aircraft. \n\nAfter having served as a technology demonstrator for [[Packard]], the [[Packard DR-980]] Diesel powered CA-3E NC8451 was re-engined with a [[Wright J-6 Whirlwind]] and exported to [[Argentina]] for use by [[Aeroposta Argentina]] in 1931. In 1934 it made a flight over [[Buenos Aires]] with Cardinal Monsignor Pacelli, shortly before he was elected as [[Pope Pius XII]], becoming the first Pope to have made a flight in an aircraft.<ref name=goldenwingsmuseum>{{cite web|author=Various|title=1929 Buhl Sport Airsedan|work=www.goldenwingsmuseum.com|url=http://www.goldenwingsmuseum.com/collection/AC-Pages/Buhl.htm|date=1 December 2015|accessdate=28 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAfter a career spent seeking out forest fires in the northern [[Ontario]] bush, as an airborne counterpart to [[fire lookout tower]]s, the last of the Ontario Provincial Air Service CA-6Ms would be sold off to private operators in 1948.<ref name=OPAS/> Their service predated the use of aircraft for directly extinguishing fires, so after spotting a fire, the Buhls would transport firemen to the fire, equipped with portable firefighting equipment, supplanting or replacing earlier types of aircraft such as the [[Curtiss HS-2L]] and [[Canadian Vickers Vedette]]. If this sounds laborious, aircraft replaced the [[canoe]]s which had been used previously. \n\nAfter passing through a number of owners and undergoing unspecified modifications ostensibly for movie photography, CA-6 NC9629 was seized on 9 May 1933 while smuggling {{cvt|660|l|usgal|order=flip}} of alcohol from [[Mexico]] during [[Prohibition in the United States|Prohibition]] near [[Fallbrook, California]] by the American [[Immigration and Naturalization Service]] while the alcohol was being transferred to a waiting [[Marmon Motor Car Company|Marmon coupe]].<ref name=Bleneau2>Bleneau, Les berlines Buhl (Seconde et derni\u00e8re partie), p.3</ref> Prohibition would end later that same year.\n\n[[Lineas Aereas del Balsas]] imported one CA-6, and [[Carlos Panini]] imported four CA-6s into Mexico for airline work, however during the 1929 [[Escobar Rebellion]] when the Mexican government faced a large scale mutiny led by General [[Jos\u00e9 Gonzalo Escobar]] against the office of President going to a civilian, one of these was operated by the [[Mexican Air Force|''Fuerza A\u00e9rea Mexicana'']] as a light utility transport with standard military red-white-green triangle markings.<ref name=Hagedorn>Hagedorn, 2006, p.37</ref> It is likely the sole example to have seen military service.\n\n==Variants==\n[[File:Packard company demonstrator Buhl CA-3E Airsedan powered with DR-980 diesel, in flight.jpg|thumb|[[Packard DR-980]] demonstrator CA-3E NC8451 in flight]]\n[[File:Buhl CA-5A N1451 (cropped).jpg|thumb|CA-5A N1451 was operated by Mamer Flying Service]]\n[[File:Buhl CA-8 Senior Airsedan NX7705.jpg|thumb|Buhl CA-8 Senior Airsedan with airliner seat parachute advertising]]\n* '''CA-3 Airsedan''' (1928) - {{cvt|36|ft|0|in|m}} [[wing span]] three-seater powered by a {{cvt|225|hp}} [[Wright R-790 Whirlwind|Wright J-5 Whirlwind]] [[radial engine|radial]]\n**'''CA-3A''' - conversion of CA-3\n**'''CA-3B Junior Airsedan''' - {{cvt|110|hp}} [[Warner Scarab]]\n**'''CA-3C Sport Airsedan''' (ATC 46) - {{cvt|225|hp}} Wright J-5 Whirlwind<ref name=Juptner1962p123>Juptner, 1962, p.123-124</ref>\n***'''CA-3CW Sport Airsedan''' (ATC 2-328) - {{cvt|300|hp}} [[Pratt & Whitney Wasp]]\n**'''CA-3D Sport Airsedan'''  (ATC 163, 2-72) - {{cvt|300|hp}} [[Wright R-975 Whirlwind|Wright J-6 Whirlwind]]<ref name=Juptner1964p>Juptner, 1964, p.179-181</ref>\n**'''CA-3E Sport Airsedan''' (ATC 2-309) - {{cvt|225|hp}} [[Packard DR-980]]\n\n* '''CA-5 Airsedan''' (1927, ATC 12) - {{cvt|42|ft|0|in|m}} wing span five-seater powered by a {{cvt|225|hp}} Wright J-5 Whirlwind<ref name=Juptner1962p44>Juptner, 1962, p.44-45</ref>\n** '''CA-5A Airsedan''' (ATC 33) - Deluxe version powered with a {{cvt|225|hp}} Wright J-5 Whirlwind<ref name=Juptner1962p96>Juptner, 1962, p.96-97</ref>\n\n* '''CA-6 Standard Airsedan''' (1929, ATC 128, 2-51) - {{cvt|40|ft|0|in|m}} wing span six-seater powered by a {{cvt|300|hp}} Wright J-6 Whirlwind<ref name=Juptner1964p81>Juptner, 1964, p.81-84</ref>\n** '''CA-6 Special'''   - {{cvt|300|hp}} Wright J-6 Whirlwind ''Spokane Sun God'' endurance aircraft\n** '''CA-6A Airsedan''' - {{cvt|420|hp}} Pratt & Whitney Wasp\n** '''CA-6B Airsedan''' (ATC 2-225) - {{cvt|450|hp}} Pratt & Whitney Wasp\n** '''CA-6D Special''' - 2 converted from '''CA-3D''' as six seaters\n** '''CA-6J Airsedan''' (ATC 2-336) - {{cvt|300|hp}} Pratt & Whitney Wasp five seater (1 converted from CA-6)\n** '''CA-6M Airsedan''' - {{cvt|440|hp}} Pratt & Whitney Wasp powered Canadian-built CA-6 with local modifications. 4 built.<ref name=OPAS/><ref name=GoldenYearsCF-4/>\n** '''CA-6W Airsedan''' (ATC 2-133) - {{cvt|420|hp}} Pratt & Whitney Wasp four seater (1 converted from CA-6)\n\n* '''CA-8 Senior Airsedan''' (1929 ATC 2-46) - {{cvt|48|ft|0|in|m}} wing span eight-seater powered by a {{cvt|450|hp}} Pratt & Whitney Wasp C\n** '''CA-8A Senior Airsedan''' (ATC 98) - {{cvt|525|hp}} [[Wright Cyclone series|Wright R-1750 Cyclone 9]]<ref name=Juptner1962p241>Juptner, 1962, p.241-242</ref>\n** '''CA-8B Senior Airsedan''' (ATC 99) - {{cvt|525|hp}} [[Pratt & Whitney R-1690 Hornet]]<ref name=Juptner1962p243>Juptner, 1962, p.243-244</ref>\n\n==Operators==\n[[File:Buhl CA-6 Airsedan Aero Digest January,1930.jpg|thumb|CA-6 CF-AAY operated by [[Cherry Red Airline]]]]\n[[File:Buhl CA-6B NC8449 sn 54 operated by Central Airlines.jpg|thumb|CA-6B NC8449 operated by [[Capital Airlines (United States)|Central Airlines]]]]\n;{{ARG}}\n*[[Aeroposta Argentina]] - operated one CA-3D<ref name=goldenwingsmuseum/>\n\n;{{flag|Canada|1921}}\n*[[Brooks Airways|Brooks Construction & Transportation/Brooks Airways]] - operated two CA-6s<ref name=GoldenYearsCF-2>Pentland, Civil Aircraft Register - Canada (CF-), p.3</ref>\n*[[Cherry Red Airline]] - operated one CA-6<ref name=GoldenYearsCF-1>Pentland, Civil Aircraft Register - Canada (CF-), p.1</ref>\n*[[National Air Transport]] - operated one CA-3C, one CA-5, and one CA-6<ref name=GoldenYearsCF-1/><ref name=GoldenYearsGC-1>Pentland, Civil Aircraft Register - Canada (G-C) p.1</ref>\n*[[Ontario Provincial Air Service|Ontario Provincial Air Service (OPAS)]] - operated four CA-6Ms<ref name=GoldenYearsCF-4>Pentland, Civil Aircraft Register - Canada (CF-), p.5</ref>\n\n;{{flag|Mexico|1934}}\n*[[Lineas Aereas del Balsas]] operated one CA-6<ref name=PentlandMexico>Pentland, Civil Aircraft Register - Mexico, p.1</ref>\n*[[Carlos Panini|Servicio A\u00e9reo Panini]] operated four CA-6s<ref name=PentlandMexico/>\n*[[Mexican Air Force|''Fuerza A\u00e9rea Mexicana'']] operated one CA-6 during the 1929 [[Escobar Rebellion]]<ref name=Hagedorn/>\n\n;{{US}}\n*[[Capital Airlines (United States)|Central Airlines]] operated a CA-6B\n*[[Nick Mamer|Nick Mamer/Mamer Air Transport/Mamer Flying Service]] - operated one CA-3A, one CA-5A, three CA-6Bs and the CA-6 distance record aircraft<ref name=PentlandUS-4>Pentland, Civil Aircraft Register - US, p.4</ref><ref name=PentlandUS-18>Pentland, Civil Aircraft Register - US, p.18</ref>\n*Various private operators.\n\n==Survivors and aircraft on display==\n[[File:Buhl CA-3C (N5860) (cropped).jpg|thumb|First CA-3 built, NC5860 in 2012]]\n*'''NC5861''': The prototype CA-3, having been converted to a CA-3C, was bought back by the Buhl family in 2007 and restored to flying condition in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|title=A Rare chance to see a Rare Buhl|url=http://www.airventure.org/news/2012/120722_rare-chance-to-see-buhl.html|accessdate=17 August 2012}}</ref>\n*'''NC8451''': A [[Packard DR-980]] [[Aircraft diesel engine|diesel]] powered CA-3 currently owned by the [[Golden Wings Museum]] in [[Blaine, Minnesota]] after having been restored from derelict condition as found in Argentina. This was the aircraft in which the first flight made by a Pope, Pius XII.<ref name=goldenwingsmuseum/> Although painted as it was when it was a CA-3E, it is fitted with the Wright J-6 engine which it had when it was a CA-3D.\n*'''CF-OAR''' and '''CF-OAT''': The unrestored remains from two OPAS Buhl CA-6Ms are on display as found, at the [[Canadian Bushplane Heritage Centre]] in [[Sault Ste. Marie, Ontario|Sault Ste. Marie]], [[Ontario]].<ref name=OPAS/>\n\n==Specifications (CA-6 ATC# 128)==\n[[File:Buhl CA-6 Airsedan 3-view Aero Digest March 1929.png|thumb|Buhl CA-6 Airsedan 3-view drawing]]\n[[File:Buhl CA-5 Airsedan 3-view drawing Aero Digest June 1927.jpg|thumb|Buhl CA-5 Airsedan 3-view drawing]]\n{{Aircraft specs\t<!--[[Template:Aircraft specs]]-->\n|ref=Juptner, 1964, p.82<!-- reference -->\n|prime units?=imp\t<!-- imp for US/UK aircraft, met(ric) for all others. REQUIRED-->\n|crew=One (pilot)\n|capacity=Five\t\t<!--passenger or cargo, not crew-->\n|length ft=29\n|length in=8\n|upper span ft=40\n|upper span in=0\n|upper span note=<br />\n*'''Upper wing chord:''' {{cvt|81|in|m|2}}\n|lower span ft=26\n|lower span in=1\n|lower span note=<br />\n*'''Lower wing chord:''' {{cvt|46|in|m|2}} mean - tapered\n|height ft=8\n|height in=7\n|wing area sqft=315\n|wing area note=combined upper and lower<br/>\n*'''Upper wing area:''' {{cvt|239|sqft}}\n*'''Lower wing area:''' {{cvt|76|sqft}}\n*'''Undercarriage track:''' {{cvt|9|ft|6|in|m}}\n|airfoil=[[Clark Y]]<ref name=Airfoil>{{cite web|last=Lednicer|first=David |title=The Incomplete Guide to Airfoil Usage|url=https://m-selig.ae.illinois.edu/ads/aircraft.html|website=m-selig.ae.illinois.edu|date=15 September 2010|accessdate=16 April 2019}}</ref>\n<!-- Weights -->\n|empty weight lb=2478\n|gross weight lb=4200\n|fuel capacity={{cvt|100|USGAL}} \n|more general=<br />\n*'''Oil Capacity:''' {{cvt|8|USGAL}}\n<!-- Powerplant -->\n|eng1 number=1\n|eng1 name=[[Wright J-6-9]] Whirlwind\n|eng1 type=Air cooled 9 cylinder [[radial engine]]\n|eng1 hp=300\n|eng1 note=\n|power original=\n|prop blade number=2\n|prop name=metal [[Hamilton Standard]] propeller\n|prop dia ft=\n|prop dia in=\n<!-- Performance -->\n|max speed mph=140\n|cruise speed mph=120\n|minimum control speed mph=45\n|range miles=720\n|ceiling ft=17,000\n|climb rate ftmin=900\n|climb rate note=in first minute\n}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Aviation}}\n* [[Buhl CA-1 Airster]]\n* [[Buhl Bull Pup]]\n{{aircontent\n<!-- include as many lines are appropriate. additional lines/entries with carriage return. -->\n|similar aircraft=<!-- similar or comparable aircraft -->\n* [[Bellanca CH-300 Pacemaker]]\n* [[Br\u00e9guet 26T]]\n* [[Cunningham-Hall PT-6]]\n* [[Solar MS-1]]\n* [[Stearman CAB-1 Coach]]\n|lists=<!-- related lists -->\n*[[List of civil aircraft]]\n|see also=<!-- other relevant information -->\n*[[Bush plane]]\n*[[Aerial firefighting]]\n}}\n\n==References==\n===Citations===\n{{reflist|1}}\n===Bibliography===\n*{{cite magazine|last=Anderson|first=Capt. Douglas E.|title=On the Step with Edo|magazine=CAHS Journal|pages=15-22 and 35-37|date=Spring 1990}}\n*{{cite web|last=Bleneau|first=Jean-Louis|title=Les berlines Buhl (Premi\u00e8re partie)|url=http://richard.ferriere.free.fr/bleneau/buhl1/buhl1.pdf|work=richard.ferriere.free.fr|language=french|date=|accessdate=30 January 2020|url-status=live}}\n*{{cite web|last=Bleneau|first=Jean-Louis|title=Les berlines Buhl (Seconde et derni\u00e8re partie)| url=http:/